HEADWORD: Chaise
<hw>Chaise</hw> <pr>(sh⟦amac⟧z)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>chaise</ets> seat, or chair, chaise or carriage, for
<ets>chaire</ets>, from a peculiar Parisian pronunciation. See
<er>Chair</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A two-wheeled carriage for two
persons, with a calash top, and the body hung on leather straps, or
thorough-braces. It is usually drawn by one horse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <mark>Loosely</mark>, <def>a carriage in general.</def>
<rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Chaja</ent>⟦br⟧
